<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="141" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="141">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="141">
<taxonomicName authorityName="K. Hori &amp; Khine" authorityYear="2022" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Polypodiaceae" genus="Thylacopteris" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Thylacopteris minuta" order="Polypodiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="141" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="minuta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="141">Thylacopteris minuta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName class="Polypodiopsida" family="Dryopteridaceae" genus="T." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="T. papillosa" order="Polypodiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="141" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="papillosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="141">T. papillosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with 20-40 sclerenchyma strands per rhizome in cross-section. However, 
<taxonomicName class="Polypodiopsida" family="Dryopteridaceae" genus="T." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="T. minuta" order="Polypodiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="141" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="minuta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="141">T. minuta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinct from 
<taxonomicName class="Polypodiopsida" family="Dryopteridaceae" genus="T." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="T. papillosa" order="Polypodiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="141" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="papillosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="141">T. papillosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with sori shallowly sunken vs. 
<taxonomicName class="Polypodiopsida" family="Dryopteridaceae" genus="T." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="T. papillosa" order="Polypodiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="141" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="papillosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="141">T. papillosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sori deeply sunken. In addition, the lamina of 
<taxonomicName class="Polypodiopsida" family="Dryopteridaceae" genus="T." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="T. minuta" order="Polypodiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="141" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="minuta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="141">T. minuta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a maximal length of 15 cm vs. a maximal length of 59 cm in 
<taxonomicName class="Polypodiopsida" family="Dryopteridaceae" genus="T." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="T. papillosa" order="Polypodiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="141" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="papillosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="141">T. papillosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="K. Hori &amp; Khine" authorityYear="2022" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Polypodiaceae" genus="Thylacopteris" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Thylacopteris minuta" order="Polypodiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="141" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="minuta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="141">Thylacopteris minuta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinct from the New Guinea endemic 
<taxonomicName class="Polypodiopsida" family="Dryopteridaceae" genus="T." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="T. diaphana" order="Polypodiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="141" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="diaphana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="141">T. diaphana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which lacks sclerenchyma strands in the rhizome, has superficial sori, and lamina with a maximal length of 45 cm.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
